<section>
    <h1>The CfP process</h1>

    <section id="rationale">
        <h2>Rationale</h2>
        <p>
            The CfP was designed with the following goals in mind:
        </p>

        <ul>
            <li>Encourage proposal submissions by everyone (irrespective of publicity, gender, race, domain etc).</li>
            <li>Encourage refinements on proposals.</li>
            <li>Make sure that the selection process is neutral and unbiased.</li>
            <li>Make sure that the most interesting proposals are actually selected by the community.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="process-overview">
        <h2>The process overview</h2>
        <p>
            The process is an amalgamation of
            <a href="http://vestibule.rubymanor.org/the-vestibule-process" target="_blank">Ruby Manor's ‘Vestibule’ process</a>,
            <a href="https://github.com/euruko2012/call-for-proposals" target="_blank">last year’s EuRuKo</a>
            and our own ideas and favourite picks from various conferences we have attended ourselves in the past.

            The main ideas are rather simple:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>Make it safe and easy for everyone to submit their proposal.</li>
            <li>Gather, discuss and refine a lot of ideas in an anonymous (blind) way without prejudice.</li>
            <li>Make a shortlist of the best proposals using some “interestingness” criteria.</li>
            <li>Publicly vote for the presentations that you want to see.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Phase 1: Submission and discussion</h3>
        <p>
            The CfP platform opens for submissions and everyone can submit unlimited number of proposals.
            During this period everyone can interact with the proposals which means:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>Discuss</li>
            <li>Promote/Demote</li>
            <li>Share on social media</li>
            <li>Refine</li>
            <li>Withdraw</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            During Phase 1 proposals show up <strong>without revealing the name of the submitter or any other
            “interestingness” information</strong>. This is in order to avoid any bias and to help people
            focus on the content of the proposal.
        </p>
        <p>
            We want to encourage <strong>everyone</strong> to participate in <%= Settings.event_name %>
            as fully as possible and one of the ways we can ensure that everyone is treated equally
            is by not revealing who is behind each proposal.
        </p>

        <h3>Interlude: Submissions freeze &amp; final call for shortlist selection</h3>
        <p>
            At a certain date (TBA) submissions close and everyone can interact with the proposals only
            for the purpose of making a final shortlist on which the final voting will take place.
            "Interacting" means:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>Promote/Demote</li>
            <li>Share on social media</li>
            <li>Withdraw</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Phase 2: Final voting &amp; selection</h3>
        <p>
            A formal second round of voting then takes place on the proposals that made it into the shortlist.
            The main difference with Phase 1 is that now <strong>there is no commenting</strong>
            and that the proposals are <strong>de-anonymized</strong>
            (this is also true for proposals that didn’t make the cut).
        </p>
    </section>

